0d9d3203-77c3-459a-bb59-ad4e4c15f99d.4f212627-cde0-4a80-b9e2-81c47fc6e031.description=
Waits for the number of seconds specified in the  input.

Inputs\:

Results\:

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
0d9d3203-77c3-459a-bb59-ad4e4c15f99d.54467e86-89ec-407a-bf78-7aea76a79ee2.description=
Checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The  input is the string that is checked for matching the  expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Examples\: If  is “RegEx”, the  input is a regular expression like\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. A message stating whether the  string matches .

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
0d9d3203-77c3-459a-bb59-ad4e4c15f99d.91e8631c-fd40-4ce3-bf74-16ebb12fa153.description=Counts from one number to another number. 
Inputs\:
from - The number to start counting at.
to - The number to count to.
incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. If unspecified this is 1. If you wanted to count 2,4,6,8 this would be 2.
reset - If true, then the counter will restart counting from the beginning.

NOTE\: These values must be between -9223372036854775808 and 9223372036854775807

Returns\:
The number that was just counted.

Note\: the primary result is resultString, Result can also be used. result (All lower case) should not be used as it is the response code.

Responses\:
has more - Not yet done counting.
no more - Done counting. This will only be returned once, then counting restarts.
failure - Something went wrong.

0d9d3203-77c3-459a-bb59-ad4e4c15f99d.c0696759-33ce-4fe9-b611-7994f1862bdd.description=
Runs an existing script, specified by name, against a device or group of devices. The proper variant of the script will be applied to each device. If no variant of the script supports a given device, that device will be skipped. The script is run as a system task.

Inputs\:
    coreHost - The DNS name or IP Address of your NAS core.
    corePort - The port to connect to your NAS core on.
    coreProtocol - The protocol to connect to your NAS core with.
Valid values\: http, https
    coreUsername - The username for the NAS core.
    corePassword - The password for the NAS user.
    scriptName - Script / command name
    isAdvanced - Should the command be an advanced script?
Valid values\: True, False
Default value\: False
    ip - The IP address of the network device.
    variables - A list of variables to be replaced in the script. These are provided as a list of name\=value pairs, separated by commas. Values can be surrounded in single-quotes ('). Within a quoted value, a single-quote can be embedded with two single-quote characters. 
Examples\: "variable1\=value1, varable2\='this is ''value 2'''"
    returnImmediately - A boolean value which controls how the command script is run. A value of true, 0, or yes, will cause the operation to return once the command script is scheduled. A value of false, 1, or no, will cause the operation to wait until the script has been run before it returns.
    parameters - Command line parameters for the script to run. Ignored for regular command scripts.
    lineByLine - Prefer to deploy line by line rather than file-based deployment. Ignored for advanced scripts, required by regular command scripts.
    startDate - Date of the start of the task.
    groupName - The group name of a list of networked devices.
    repeat - (\#min | \#\:\# | \#days | \#weeks | \#months) where \# is a positive integer. \#\:\# is hours\:minutes; The two integers do not have to be the same.
    comment - The comment to tie to this action.
    presnapshot - Possible values\: true or false. If false, this indicates that the snapshot that runs before the script should be skipped.
    postsnapshot - Possible valuse\: true, false or task. If false, this indicates that the snapshot that runs after the script should be skipped. If "task", this indicates that snapshot after the script should run as a separate task.
    timeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete.
Default value\: 90000 (90 seconds).

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Text result of NAS script run
    commandStatus - The status of the NAS command.
    text - The response text of the NAS command.
    stackTrace - The stack trace (If any) of the NAS command.

Notes\:
1) Start date must be in one of the following formats\: 
YYYY-MM-DD HH\:MM\:SS     e.g. 2002-09-06 12\:30\:00 
YYYY-MM-DD HH\:MM        e.g. 2002-09-06 12\:30
YYYY-MM-DD              e.g. 2002-09-06 
YYYY/MM/DD              e.g. 2002/09/06 
YYYY\:MM\:DD\:HH\:MM        e.g. 2002\:09\:06\:12\:30
Or, one of\: now, today, yesterday, tomorrow 
Or, in the format\: "  " e.g. "3 days ago"  is a positive integer; is one of\: seconds, minutes, hours, days, weeks, months, years; is one of\: ago, before, later, after.
